  "honest_reading": "OligoForge's exhaustive Python design is 65x-314x slower than Primer3's C core on the same templates (slower on all 18). The slowdown is driven mainly by template length (r(len,OF ms)=0.49) and candidate count; GC contributes weakly-to-moderately (r(GC,ratio)=0.38) via the anneal gate (D2) admitting more GC-rich candidates -- the extreme is clean (most-AT-rich plas_cytb_ATrich 114.2x vs most-GC-rich Mtb_rpoB_GCrich 314.9x) but it is NOT a monotone GC law. Absolute design cost (1281-5967 ms on a 1-core x86_64 host) is fine for interactive single-assay use, the tool's actual scope; it is NOT a batch/genome-scale design engine. The specificity scan is linear (R^2=0.9999, ~10.1 us/bp): fine for transcriptomes and small genomes, impractical for a whole 3.2 Gb human genome (~9 h projected) -- which is why specificity is checked against a supplied FASTA, not claimed genome-wide."
